## 2. Documentation Standards

**Hotlinking Rule:** When a variable name appears in any narrative document ([architecture.md](architecture.md), [protocol.md](protocol.md), [intent.md](intent.md), or any other prose document), it should be formatted as a code reference (backtick-wrapped) and linked to its glossary entry in this document. This allows any planner, developer, or agent reading the documentation to immediately reference the authoritative definition.

**Inline Schema Definitions:** JSON Schema documents use the `"description"` field on every property as the inline documentation mechanism. The description string serves as the co-located definition so that a reader does not need to cross-reference multiple documents to understand a schema. This replaces the earlier collapsible-div approach and is the canonical way to document schema variables inline.

**Glossary Inclusion Rule:** Every variable name that appears in any schema definition anywhere in the project must be added to the Glossary (section 4 of this document). No variable may exist in a schema without a corresponding glossary entry. The glossary entry must include the variable name, type, description, which schema(s) it appears in, and whether it is required or optional.

**Consistency Enforcement:** During specification review, any variable name that does not match the naming conventions in section 1 or is missing from the glossary is a blocking issue that must be resolved before the specification is considered complete.

