### 4.1 Protocol-Level Variables

These variables appear in the trilateral handshake flow, challenge tokens, and signed payloads. They are the core vocabulary of the UNS protocol.

<details>
<summary><code>nonce</code> — string — Unique, time-limited cryptographic challenge for replay protection.</summary>

**Required.** A 32-byte hex value (64 characters) generated per-handshake. Provides replay protection; each handshake is unique and time-bound. Consumed on use; must never be reused. Default TTL is 300–600 seconds (spec says "should"; see adversarial review S-MIN-4 for hardening recommendation).

**Sources:** [receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md](../specs/receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md), [cryptographic_operations_specification.md](../specs/cryptographic_operations_specification.md), [gateway_infrastructure.md](../specs/gateway_infrastructure.md) (KV nonce tracking), [uns_handshake_sequence_and_failure_points.md](../specs/uns_handshake_sequence_and_failure_points.md)

**Open issue:** Nonce generation ownership is disputed across documents (see adversarial review P-CRIT-1). Must be resolved before Phase 1.
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>nonce_consumed_at</code> — ISO 8601 timestamp — When the nonce was atomically consumed by the Gateway.</summary>

**Optional.** Recorded at the moment the Gateway successfully invokes the atomic delete operation on the KV nonce key. Used for forensic auditing and debugging nonce replay scenarios. Not part of the signed protocol; recorded only in Gateway internal logs.

**Sources:** [gateway_infrastructure.md](../specs/gateway_infrastructure.md) (section 4.4, atomic nonce consumption)

**Related:** `nonce`, `created_at`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>attestation_level_required</code> — string — Attestation level the service demands for this request.</summary>

**Required.** Embedded by the Gateway in the challenge token. Expressed as an OOB method name from the hierarchy (e.g., `session_only`, `device_signature`). Determined per-request by the Gateway's policy evaluation engine based on registered service rules or dynamic overrides. Never falls below `minimum_attestation_level`.

**Sources:** [gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md](../specs/gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md), [receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md](../specs/receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md), [guardian_policy_evaluation_engine.md](../specs/guardian_policy_evaluation_engine.md), [gateway_infrastructure.md](../specs/gateway_infrastructure.md) (D1 service_rules, receipts)

**Related:** `attestation_level_provided`, `minimum_attestation_level`, `applicable_rule`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>attestation_level_provided</code> — string — Attestation level the Guardian actually collected.</summary>

**Required.** Embedded by the Guardian when signing the response token. Expressed as an OOB method name. Must meet or exceed `attestation_level_required` for the handshake to succeed. If insufficient, the Gateway returns `UNS_ATTESTATION_LEVEL_MISMATCH`.

**Sources:** [guardian_policy_evaluation_engine.md](../specs/guardian_policy_evaluation_engine.md), [receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md](../specs/receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md), [gateway_infrastructure.md](../specs/gateway_infrastructure.md) (D1 receipts)

**Related:** `attestation_level_required`, `oob_method_used`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>oob_method_used</code> — string — The specific OOB method performed during the handshake.</summary>

**Required.** The method the Guardian used to satisfy the attestation requirement (e.g., `device_signature`, `biometric`, `totp`), or `none` if `session_only`. Embedded inside the Guardian's signed payload. Neither Service nor Gateway possesses the user's public key — they trust the Guardian's assertion.

**Sources:** [guardian_role.md](../specs/guardian_role.md), [receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md](../specs/receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md), [guardian_infrastructure.md](../specs/guardian_infrastructure.md) (D1 receipts), [gateway_infrastructure.md](../specs/gateway_infrastructure.md) (D1 receipts)

**Related:** `oob_auth_methods`, `supported_oob_methods`, `attestation_level_provided`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>applicable_rule</code> — string (JSON) — Which service rule produced the attestation requirement.</summary>

**Required in receipt.** JSON description of the rule that generated `attestation_level_required` for this request. Preserves auditability — any receipt can be traced back to the policy decision that triggered it. May describe a registered rule, dynamic override, or default floor.

**Sources:** [gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md](../specs/gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md), [gateway_infrastructure.md](../specs/gateway_infrastructure.md) (D1 receipts), [guardian_infrastructure.md](../specs/guardian_infrastructure.md) (D1 receipts)

**Related:** `attestation_level_required`, `rule_source`, `rule_type`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>rule_source</code> — string — Origin of the attestation requirement decision.</summary>

**Required in audit log.** One of: `registered_rule`, `dynamic_override`, or `default_floor`. Distinguishes whether the `attestation_level_required` came from a pre-registered service rule, a per-request override from the service, or the `minimum_attestation_level` floor.

**Sources:** [gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md](../specs/gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md)

**Related:** `applicable_rule`, `attestation_level_required`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>issued_at</code> — ISO 8601 timestamp — When the Guardian signed the token.</summary>

**Required.** UTC timestamp marking when the Guardian's signature was applied, completing the trilateral handshake. Used for receipt ordering, expiration calculations, and audit trails.

**Sources:** [receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md](../specs/receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md), [guardian_role.md](../specs/guardian_role.md), [guardian_infrastructure.md](../specs/guardian_infrastructure.md) (D1 receipts)
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>agent_id</code> — string — Identifier for the agent initiating the handshake.</summary>

**Required in challenge.** Identifies which agent is requesting access. Appears in challenge payloads and audit logs. The agent has a keypair from onboarding but does not sign the authentication token — agent keypair role is reserved for future specification.

**Sources:** [cryptographic_operations_specification.md](../specs/cryptographic_operations_specification.md), [uns_handshake_sequence_and_failure_points.md](../specs/uns_handshake_sequence_and_failure_points.md)

**Open issue:** Agent binding strength is underspecified (see adversarial review S-MAJ-7).
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>action</code> — string — The specific service action or feature being requested.</summary>

**Context-dependent.** The feature, operation, or resource the agent is requesting access to. Used by the Gateway's policy engine to match against service rules and determine `attestation_level_required`. Service-defined vocabulary; not standardized by UNS.

**Sources:** [gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md](../specs/gateway_policy_evaluation_engine.md), [cryptographic_operations_specification.md](../specs/cryptographic_operations_specification.md)

**Related:** `rule_type`, `attestation_level_required`
</details>

<details>
<summary><code>extensions</code> — object — Optional forward-compatibility container for non-protocol extensions.</summary>

**Optional.** A top-level object present in all UNS JSON schemas (service manifests, receipts, attestation rules, challenge tokens, etc.). Contains vendor-specific or future protocol extensions as key-value pairs. Excluded from canonical serialization (not signed).

**Parser Behavior:** Implementations MUST ignore unknown keys inside `extensions` (fail-open). Encountering an extension the parser doesn't recognize must not cause rejection or error — simply skip it. This ensures old implementations can process messages from newer implementations.

**Naming Convention:**
- Vendor/custom extensions: reverse domain prefix — `com.example.feature`, `org.acme.analytics`, etc.
- Future UNS protocol extensions: no prefix — `future_feature_name`, `enhanced_metadata`, etc.
- The naming convention prevents collisions between vendor extensions and future protocol additions.

**Signature Treatment:** Extensions are excluded from all cryptographic signature computations. If a field must be signed (part of protocol integrity), it cannot be an extension — it must be a top-level schema field.

**Sources:** [specification.md](../docs/specification.md) section 1.4 (Forward Compatibility Policy), [mcp_tool_definitions.md](../specs/mcp_tool_definitions.md) (service manifest), [receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md](../specs/receipt_format_and_assembly_specification.md) (receipt), [attestation_rule_schema.md](../specs/attestation_rule_schema.md) (service and Guardian rules), [guardian_mcp_tool_definitions.md](../specs/guardian_mcp_tool_definitions.md) (challenge token)

**Related:** Forward compatibility policy (specification.md 1.4)
</details>

